'''Julianne Alexandra Hough''' ({{IPAc-en|h|ʌ|f}}; born July 20, 1988)<ref name=tvgbio>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julianne-hough/bio/287155 |title=Julianne Hough: Biography |publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]] |access-date=17 March 2013 |archive-date=July 3, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703110023/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julianne-hough/bio/287155 |url-status=live }}</ref> is an American dancer, actress and television personality. In 2007, she joined the cast of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Dancing with the Stars (American TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' as a professional dancer, winning two seasons with her celebrity partners.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dance Workout Routines with Julianne Hough |url=http://www.shape.com/lifestyle/entertainment_and_celebrities/cover_models/dancing_her_heart_out_and_her_body_fit |work=[[Shape (magazine)|Shape]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807005215/http://www.shape.com/lifestyle/entertainment_and_celebrities/cover_models/dancing_her_heart_out_and_her_body_fit |archive-date=August 7, 2009}}</ref> After leaving the show in 2009, she returned in 2014 to serve as a judge on ''Dancing with the Stars'', a position she held until 2017.<ref name="Hough joins">{{cite magazine |last=Highfill |first=Samantha |date=August 21, 2014 |title=Julianne Hough joins 'Dancing With the Stars' as fourth judge|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/08/21/julianne-hough-dancing-with-the-stars-judge/ |access-date=August 21, 2014 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |location=Des Moines, IA}}</ref> She received three [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Choreography|Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for her work on the series, winning once in 2015 with her brother, [[Derek Hough]].<ref name="Emmy nominations for Julianne" />

Hough made her acting debut in the 2001 film ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', but played her first major role in the 2010 film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which was followed with leading roles as Ariel in ''[[Footloose (2011 film)|Footloose]]'' (2011), Sherrie in ''[[Rock of Ages (2012 film)|Rock of Ages]]'' (2012), and Katie in ''[[Safe Haven (film)|Safe Haven]]'' (2013). Hough portrayed Sandy in the 2016 live [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] television production of ''[[Grease Live!|Grease]]''.<ref name="grease" /> She also served as a judge on ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' for its [[America's Got Talent (season 14)|14th season]].<ref name="agt host" /> In 2022, she made her [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] theater debut in the political farce ''[[POTUS: Or, Behind Every Great Dumbass Are Seven Women Trying to Keep Him Alive]]''. In the same year, she hosted ''[[75th Tony Awards#Ceremony information|The Tony Awards: Act One]]'' alongside [[Darren Criss]]. In 2023, Hough returned to ''Dancing with the Stars'' as co-host, alongside main host [[Alfonso Ribeiro]].

==Early life==
[[File:Derek Hough & Julianne Hough 2014 Kaleidoscope Ball (cropped).jpg|thumb|Hough and her brother [[Derek Hough|Derek]] at the 2014 Kaleidoscope Ball]]
Hough was born in [[Orem, Utah]],<ref name="tvgbio married">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julianne-hough-287155/bio/ |title=Julianne Hough CELEBRITY |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |access-date=January 17, 2015 |archive-date=February 16, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216225458/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julianne-hough-287155/bio/ |url-status=live }}</ref> the youngest of five children in a [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Mormon]] family.<ref name=wecba/><ref name=hough.com>{{cite web |url=http://juliannehough.com/category/dancing/ |title=About: Dancing |publisher=JulianneHough.com |access-date=17 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220171318/http://juliannehough.com/category/dancing/ |archive-date=February 20, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=copp>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Copp |url=http://c-dh.net/articles/2007/05/25/affiliate/advertisernews/news/02dancing.txt |title=Local woman's sister dances with the stars |work=[[The Advertiser News]] |location=[[Spring Hill, Tennessee]] |date=May 25, 2007 |access-date=May 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412095214/http://c-dh.net/articles/2007/05/25/affiliate/advertisernews/news/02dancing.txt |archive-date=April 12, 2009}}</ref> Her parents are Bruce and Marianne Hough;<ref name=wecba>{{Cite news |last=Schadler |first=Jay |url=https://abcnews.go.com/2020/DancingStars/story?id=3839821&tqkw=&tqshow=2020&page=1 |title=Sibling Rivalry: A Brother and Sister Compete to Win on 'Dancing with the Stars' |work=ABC News |date=November 9, 2007 |access-date=December 22, 2010 |archive-date=March 17, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317204003/http://abcnews.go.com/2020/DancingStars/story?id=3839821&tqkw=&tqshow=2020&page=1 |url-status=live }}</ref> her father was twice chairman of the [[Utah Republican Party]] and ran for [[Utah's 2nd congressional district]] in [[2023 Utah's 2nd congressional district special election|2023]].<ref name=wetre>{{cite news |last=Benson |first=Lee |title=Country singer's roots are in Utah |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705296704/Country-singers-roots-are-in-Utah.html |work=[[Deseret News]]  |location=Salt Lake City, Utah |date=April 12, 2009 |access-date=December 22, 2010 |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927061700/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705296704/Country-singers-roots-are-in-Utah.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schott |first=Brian |work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]] |date=12 July 2023 |access-date=14 July 2023 |url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2023/07/12/three-republicans-have-qualified/ |title=Three Republicans have qualified for Utah's special GOP primary election to replace Rep. Chris Stewart}}</ref> Her brother, [[Derek Hough]], is also a professional dancer. She has three older sisters.<ref name="TVGuide">[http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julianne-hough/bio/287155n Julianne Hough News, Julianne Hough Bio and Photos | TVGuide.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021005438/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julianne-hough/bio/287155n |date=October 21, 2012}}</ref> All four of Hough's grandparents were dancers.<ref>[http://www.sweetslyrics.com/bio-Julianne%20Hough.html Sweetslyrics – Julianne Hough Biography<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002152606/http://www.sweetslyrics.com/bio-Julianne%20Hough.html |date=October 2, 2011}}</ref> She is also a second cousin of musicians [[Riker Lynch|Riker]], [[Rydel Lynch|Rydel]], [[Rocky Lynch|Rocky]], and [[Ross Lynch]] from the band [[R5 (band)|R5]], their maternal grandmothers are sisters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://instagram.com/p/nROuFnCf6b/#  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/instagram/juleshough/707411356244639387 |archive-date=2021-12-23 |url-access=subscription|title=On my way to the #rdmas to support my cousins @officialR5 good luck tonight! |date=April 27, 2014 |access-date=June 19, 2014 |publisher=Instagram |last=Hough |first=Julianne}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Francis |first=Nathan |title='Dancing With The Stars' Rumor: Ross Lynch, Cousin Of Julianne Hough, Could Be Joining Cast |url=https://www.inquisitr.com/1621366/dancing-with-the-stars-rumor-ross-lynch-cousin-of-julianne-hough-could-be-joining-cast/ |work=[[Inquisitr]] |location=New York City |date=November 9, 2014 |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=March 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305202612/https://www.inquisitr.com/1621366/dancing-with-the-stars-rumor-ross-lynch-cousin-of-julianne-hough-could-be-joining-cast/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Hough's formal training began at the Center Stage Performing Arts Studio in Orem <ref name=hough.com /> where she danced with Josh Murillo, among others, in Latin Ballroom. She began dancing competitively at nine.<ref name="Julianne Hough">{{cite web |title=Julianne Hough- Biography |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/person/julianne-hough/biography.html |work=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |date=November 16, 2010 |access-date=May 5, 2013 |archive-date=March 8, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308133218/http://movies.yahoo.com/person/julianne-hough/biography.html |url-status=live }}</ref> When she was 10, Julianne's parents, who were divorcing, sent Julianne and her brother Derek to London<ref name=wetre /><ref name=cosmo-feb2013>{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Logan |url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/exclusive/julianne-hough-february-cover |title=Julianne Hough Is Our February Cover Girl! |work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]] |date=February 2013 |access-date=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104165353/http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/exclusive/julianne-hough-february-cover |archive-date=January 4, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> to live and study with their coaches, [[Corky Ballas|Corky]] and [[Shirley Ballas]].<ref name="Julianne Hough"/> The Ballases tutored the Houghs alongside their own son, [[Mark Ballas|Mark]].<ref name="Julianne Hough"/> At the [[Italia Conti Academy of Theatre Arts]] Hough and her brother <ref name=cosmo-feb2013 /> received training in song, theatre, gymnastics and many forms of dance, including jazz, ballet, and tap.<ref name=hough.net>[http://www.juliannehough.net/bio.html Bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219135830/http://www.juliannehough.net/bio.html |date=December 19, 2008}} JulianneHough.net. Retrieved 2008-05-19.</ref> When Hough was 12, the three children formed their own pop music trio 2B1G ("2 Boys, 1 Girl").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timepiecefilms.com/expedition4am/page-44.html|title=Expedition 4 a.m. Project|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106200914/http://www.timepiecefilms.com/expedition4am/page-44.html |archive-date=January 6, 2008|publisher=Timepiece Films|access-date=2008-05-19}}</ref> They performed at dance competitions in the UK and the U.S., and showcased in a UK television show.<ref>''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' interview, October 11, 2007</ref> At 15, Hough became the youngest dancer, and the only American, to win both Junior World Latin Champion and International Latin Youth Champion at the [[Blackpool Dance Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dancevision.com/instructors/julianne_hough/ |title=Instructors:: Julianne Hough |publisher=Dancevision|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422230851/http://www.dancevision.com/instructors/julianne_hough/ |archive-date=April 22, 2007}}</ref> After returning to the U.S., she attended the [[Las Vegas Academy]] and [[Alta High School (Utah)|Alta High School]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Sonya |last=Padgett |url=http://www.lvrj.com/living/7042667.html |title=Dancing her way to fame |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |publisher=News + Media Capital Group LLC|location=Las Vegas, Nevada|date=April 16, 2007|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=October 14, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014005710/http://www.lvrj.com/living/7042667.html}}</ref>

==Career==

[[File:JulianneHoughMarch09.jpg|thumb|right|Hough performing in March 2009]]
Hough was one of the Million Dollar Dancers in the 2006 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] game show called ''[[Show Me the Money (U.S. game show)|Show Me the Money]]''. She won [[Dancing with the Stars (American TV series) season 4|season four]] of the U.S. edition of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (American TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' with her partner, [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold medal-winning speed skater [[Apolo Ohno]], making Hough the youngest professional dancer to win on the program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/profile/julianne-hough.aspx|title=Julianne Hough Bio – BuddyTV|access-date=March 21, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001022638/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/profile/julianne-hough.aspx|archive-date=October 1, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Blickley |first=Leigh |date=2016-04-13 |title=How Julianne Hough Is Taking Control Of Her Career |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/how-julianne-hough-is-taking-control-of-her-career_n_570bd432e4b0836057a1c3d1 |access-date=2023-10-04 |website=HuffPost |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Crucchiola |first=Jordan |date=2016-08-26 |title=Julianne and Derek Hough Will Return to Lord Over Dancing With the Stars for Season 23 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/08/houghs-will-triumphantly-return-to-dwts.html |access-date=2023-10-04 |website=Vulture |language=en}}</ref> On November 27, 2007, Hough and her partner, three-time [[Indianapolis 500]] champion [[Hélio Castroneves]], became the winners of season five. Hough returned for season six with radio host/comedian [[Adam Carolla]], but they were eliminated in week four. In July 2008, Hough was nominated at the [[60th Primetime Emmy Awards]] in the category of "[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Choreography|Outstanding Choreography]]" for her mambo "Para Los Rumberos" (performed with partner Hélio Castroneves) on ''Dancing with the Stars''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmys.tv/awards/2008pte/60thpte_noms.php |title=60th Annual Emmy Nominations |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |access-date=August 25, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413013409/http://www.emmys.tv/awards/2008pte/60thpte_noms.php |archive-date=April 13, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

On August 25, 2008, the cast of [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|season seven]] was announced, and Hough was partnered with ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' actor [[Cody Linley]]. She felt abdominal pains during their jitterbug performance on October 21, 2008, and she was immediately rushed to a hospital 40 minutes after the encore performance.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2008-10-27 |title='Dancing With the Stars': Julianne Hough to have appendix removed |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/blogs/show-tracker/story/2008-10-27/dancing-with-the-stars-julianne-hough-to-have-appendix-removed |access-date=2023-10-07 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news |title='DWTS' pro Julianne Hough to have appendix removed |url=https://abc7news.com/archive/6474103/ |access-date=2023-10-07 |work=ABC7 San Francisco |language=en}}</ref> She subsequently had surgery to have her appendix removed after being diagnosed with [[endometriosis]], causing her to miss several performances, [[Edyta Śliwińska]] stood in for her. Hough returned to the show, although the pair was ultimately eliminated in the semi-finals. She appeared on the November 12 results show dancing the [[Jive (dance)|jive]] to "[[Great Balls of Fire]]" with her brother for the "Design-A-Dance" contest.

On November 20, 2008, Hough was on [[Ryan Seacrest]]'s radio show, ''On Air with Ryan Seacrest''. She announced that, in order to further her music career, she would not be returning to ''Dancing with the Stars'' for the foreseeable future.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Dehnart|author-link=Andy Dehnart|url=https://www.realityblurred.com/realitytv/2008/11/dancing-with-the-stars-7-julianne_hough_leaving/|title=Julianne Hough leaving Dancing with the Stars because "music is where I want to be"|work=[[Reality Blurred]]|date=November 20, 2008|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305202657/https://www.realityblurred.com/realitytv/2008/11/dancing-with-the-stars-7-julianne_hough_leaving/|url-status=live}}</ref> However, she did return for one final time in season eight, partnering with country singer [[Chuck Wicks]]. They were voted off in week eight of the competition and came in sixth place. They then began dating after the season was over.<ref>{{cite news|title=Did You Know These Dancing with the Stars Relationships Happened Off the Show?: Chuck Wicks and Julianne Hough|url=http://www.eonline.com/photos/13686/did-you-know-these-dancing-with-the-stars-relationships-happened-off-the-show/416441|work=[[E! Online]]|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305143023/http://www.eonline.com/photos/13686/did-you-know-these-dancing-with-the-stars-relationships-happened-off-the-show/416441|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 11, 2011, Hough returned to ''Dancing with the Stars'' and danced with her ''[[Footloose (2011 film)|Footloose]]'' co-star [[Kenny Wormald]] twice, and with her brother. She returned again on May 15, 2012, in a dance performance to promote her film ''[[Rock of Ages (2012 film)|Rock of Ages]]''. On October 7, 2013, she was guest judge in place of [[Len Goodman]], which was the first time a former pro dancer came back to judge. In September 2014, she returned as a permanent judge on the panel, a position she held until 2017.<ref name="Hough joins"/> She returned to the show as a guest judge in 2021, filling in for her brother Derek.

On March 20, 2023, it was announced that Hough would join ''Dancing with the Stars'' as the new co-host,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/dancing-with-the-stars-julianne-hough-replaces-tyra-banks-co-host-1235557764/|title=''Dancing With the Stars'' Vet Julianne Hough to Replace Tyra Banks as Co-Host for Season 32 (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author1=Brian Steinberg|author2=Emily Longeretta|date=March 20, 2023|access-date=March 20, 2023|archive-date=March 20, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320150026/https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/dancing-with-the-stars-julianne-hough-replaces-tyra-banks-co-host-1235557764/|url-status=live}}</ref> following [[Tyra Banks]]'s departure,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2023/03/tyra-banks-leaving-dancing-with-the-stars-1235302893/|title=Tyra Banks Is Leaving ''Dancing With The Stars''|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Lynette Rice|date=March 17, 2023|access-date=March 20, 2023|archive-date=March 19, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319225118/https://deadline.com/2023/03/tyra-banks-leaving-dancing-with-the-stars-1235302893/|url-status=live}}</ref> and that previous co-host [[Alfonso Ribeiro]] would assume Banks's old role as emcee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2023/03/dancing-with-the-stars-replaces-tyra-banks-julianne-hough-1235304599/|title=''Dancing With The Stars'' Replaces Tyra Banks With Julianne Hough|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Lynette Rice|date=March 20, 2023|access-date=March 20, 2023|archive-date=March 20, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320154059/https://deadline.com/2023/03/dancing-with-the-stars-replaces-tyra-banks-julianne-hough-1235304599/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Move Live On Tour===
On March 18, 2014, Hough and her brother Derek announced a summer tour of over 40 cities across the U.S. and Canada, called "Move Live on Tour", which would include dancing and singing from both of them, and the appearance of a group of dancers employed by the Houghs who earned their jobs through auditions.<ref>{{cite web|last1=ABC News|title=Julianne Hough and Derek Hough Announce National Tour|url=https://gma.yahoo.com/blogs/abc-news-blogs/julianne-hough-derek-hough-announce-national-tour-140624897--abc-news-tv.html|publisher=Yahoo|date=March 18, 2014|access-date=July 13, 2014|archive-date=July 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714220347/https://gma.yahoo.com/blogs/abc-news-blogs/julianne-hough-derek-hough-announce-national-tour-140624897--abc-news-tv.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> They embarked on the sold-out tour on May 25, 2014, in [[Park City, Kansas]], and ended it in [[Los Angeles]] on July 26, 2014. Due to the success of ticket sales and several sold-out venues before the tour had officially kicked off, several more shows were added to the tour schedule, which also sold out.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carbone|first1=Gina|title=Julianne and Derek Hough Add L.A. Tour Date After Move Live Sells Out Shows|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/dancing-with-the-stars/articles/2014-05-07-julianne-derek-hough-add-la|publisher=Wetpaint|date=May 8, 2014|access-date=July 14, 2014|archive-date=July 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714184554/http://www.wetpaint.com/dancing-with-the-stars/articles/2014-05-07-julianne-derek-hough-add-la|url-status=live}}</ref> For the tour choreography, the Hough siblings collaborated with [[Tabitha and Napoleon D'umo|Nappytabs]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rizzo|first1=Monica|title=Derek & Julianne Hough Will Soon Be Dancing in a City Near You|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20797902,00.html|publisher=People|date=March 18, 2014|access-date=July 13, 2014|archive-date=March 3, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222838/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20797902,00.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Following the success of the 2014 tour and high demand, the Houghs announced the return of "Move Live on Tour" in the summer of 2015. Spanning from June 12, 2015, to August 8, 2015, the sold-out tour visited over 40 cities throughout the U.S. and Canada, and visited larger venues than in the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wight|first1=Sherry|title=Derek Hough unveils summer 2015 'Move Live on Tour' dates|url=http://www.axs.com/news/derek-hough-unveils-summer-2015-move-live-on-tour-dates-42713|website=AXS|publisher=axs.com|access-date=22 November 2015|archive-date=December 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225025103/http://www.axs.com/news/derek-hough-unveils-summer-2015-move-live-on-tour-dates-42713|url-status=live}}</ref> Tabitha and Napoleon D'umo "Nappytabs" returned as collaborating choreographers alongside the Hough siblings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Move Live On Tour: About|url=http://www.moveliveontour.com/about|website=Move Live On Tour|publisher=moveliveontour.com|access-date=25 May 2016|archive-date=May 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524002847/http://www.moveliveontour.com/about|url-status=dead}}</ref> Auditions were also held to recruit a new group of dancers to join the Houghs, although some back-up dancers from the previous year returned.
[[File:Julianne Hough 2009 Concert VI.jpg|thumb|Hough performing at a George Strait Concert in 2009]]

On December 14, 2016, they announced, via social media, that they would be going on a new tour, "MOVE BEYOND Live on Tour", in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/JulianneHough/videos/10154010077586456/|title=Julianne Hough|website=[[Facebook]]|access-date=December 14, 2016|archive-date=February 13, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230213094111/https://www.facebook.com/JulianneHough/videos/10154010077586456/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Music===
Hough's first country-music single, "Will You Dance With Me", was released to [[iTunes]] and [[Wal-Mart]] in May 2007 to raise money for the [[American Red Cross]]. The song placed at number 100 on the [[Billboard Pop 100|''Billboard'' Pop 100]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|first=Christopher|last=Rocchio|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/dancing-with-stars-pro-julianne-hough-signs-country-record-deal-6193.php|title='Dancing with the Stars' pro Julianne Hough signs country record deal|work=realitytvworld.com|date=November 30, 2007|access-date=March 9, 2008|archive-date=January 10, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110073335/http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/dancing-with-stars-pro-julianne-hough-signs-country-record-deal-6193.php|url-status=live}}</ref> She later signed with [[Universal Music Group Nashville]]'s Mercury Nashville division.

Her 2008 [[Julianne Hough (album)|self-titled debut album]] was recorded in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] and produced by [[David Malloy]], who has worked with [[Reba McEntire]] and [[Eddie Rabbitt]], among others. Hough's album, which met with mixed reviews,<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/julianne-hough-mw0000784662|title=Review – ''Julianne Hough''|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=[[TiVo Corporation]]|location=New York City|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305142920/https://www.allmusic.com/album/julianne-hough-mw0000784662|url-status=live}}</ref> debuted at number one  on the [[Top Country Albums]] chart on May 31, and also peaked at number three on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Edward|last=Morris|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1588399/julianne-hough-dances-to-top-of-country-album-chart.jhtml|title=Julianne Hough dances to the top of the Top Country Albums chart|work=Country Music Television|date=May 31, 2008|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 8, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308094128/http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1588399/julianne-hough-dances-to-top-of-country-album-chart.jhtml|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hough's second single, and the first to be released to country radio, was "[[That Song in My Head]]".

[[File:Julianne Hough 2009 Birthday Bash I.jpg|thumb|Hough performing at a 2009 Birthday Bash concert|left]]Hough joined [[Brad Paisley]]'s 2008 Tour, along with [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]] and Chuck Wicks. Hough, Paisley, and [[Willie Nelson]] appeared in the video for the [[Snoop Dogg]] song "My Medicine".<ref>{{cite web|title=Snoop Dogg Video Features Willie, Brad and Julianne|url=http://theboot.com/snoop-dogg-video-features-willie-brad-and-julianne/|work=The Boot|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|location=Greenwich, Connecticut|date=July 1, 2008|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305202604/http://theboot.com/snoop-dogg-video-features-willie-brad-and-julianne/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Hough appeared in a [[Juicy Fruit]] commercial in the fall of 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dip_ThFvjKI| archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211030/Dip_ThFvjKI| archive-date=2021-10-30|title=Julianne Hough Juicy Fruit commercial |work=YouTube|location=Mountain View, California|date=September 9, 2008 |access-date=March 4, 2018}}{{cbignore}}</ref> and released an EP of [[Christmas music]] called ''[[Sounds of the Season: The Julianne Hough Holiday Collection]]''. She performed her second single "My Hallelujah Song" on ''Dancing With the Stars'' on November 18, 2008, with her brother Derek Hough, [[Mark Ballas]], and [[Lacey Schwimmer]] dancing.

Hough, [[LeAnn Rimes]], [[Jessica Simpson]], and [[Kellie Pickler]] announced the 2009 [[Academy of Country Music]] Award nominees in February 2009. Hough was nominated for the Top New Female Vocalist award, a fan-voted award, which she subsequently won.<ref>{{cite web|first=Melinda|last=Lorge|title=Sounds like Julianne Hough is ready to jump back into singing|url=https://rarecountry.com/news/sounds-like-julianne-hough-is-ready-to-jump-back-into-singing/|work=[[Rare Country]]|date=May 7, 2017|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305142755/https://rarecountry.com/news/sounds-like-julianne-hough-is-ready-to-jump-back-into-singing/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hough won the Top New Artist award at the 44th Annual Academy of Country Music Awards on April 5, 2009, and released a single, "[[Is That So Wrong]]", to country radio on June 21, 2010. It was intended as the lead single for her second album, ''Wildfire'', but the album was never released.

In June 2012, Hough told [[AOL]]'s ''The Boot'' that her second album was "completely done" and that she was initially "really, really looking forward to the record." However, she also stated that, due to the underperforming lead single and having "a lot of momentum" in her film career,  no plans have been made  to release ''Wildfire''. She does intend to resume focusing on her music career at some point, though: "I feel like when I have the time to focus on it, and when I feel like it is the right time, [I'll return to] my music," she said.<ref>{{cite web|first=Melinda|last=Newman|title=Julianne Hough, 'Rock of Ages': Multi-Talented Star Talks Tom Cruise, Baboons and Strip Clubs|url=http://www.theboot.com/2012/06/15/julianne-hough-rock-of-ages/|work=[[The Boot (website)|The Boot]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|location=Greenwich, Connecticut|date=June 15, 2012|access-date=November 15, 2012|archive-date=November 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124183802/http://www.theboot.com/2012/06/15/julianne-hough-rock-of-ages|url-status=live}}</ref> Hough's manager, Scott Siman also represents Tim McGraw.<ref name="Pollstar">{{cite web|url=https://news.pollstar.com/2008/07/18/hotstar-julianne-hough|title=Hotstar: Julianne Hough|last=Reinartz|first=Joe|date=July 18, 2008|access-date=March 22, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Full Sail">{{cite web|url=https://fullsail.edu/about/full-sail-stories/the-two-grads-who-manage-tim-mcgraws-brand|title=The Two Grads Who Manage Tim McGraw's Brand|date=October 16, 2018|access-date=March 22, 2024}}</ref>

===Acting and other appearances===
Hough's first acting role was in the 2001 feature film ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', in an uncredited role as a "[[Hogwarts]] schoolgirl".<ref name="potter-nydaily">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/harry-potter-deathly-hallows-gallery-1.5773?pmSlide=1.102302 |title='Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows': Where are they now? |work=[[Daily News (New York)]] |access-date=2011-01-25 |date=July 15, 2011 |page=15 of 20 (slide show) |archive-date=February 16, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216223304/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/harry-potter-deathly-hallows-gallery-1.5773?pmSlide=1.102302 |url-status=live }}</ref> She appeared in the 2010 musical ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', starring [[Cher]] and [[Christina Aguilera]]. In the film, which chronicles a small-town girl (Aguilera) who finds success at a Los Angeles burlesque club, Hough plays a dancer named Georgia.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joyce |last=Eng |title=Julianne Hough Joins Christina Aguilera, Cher In Burlesque |url=http://movies.tvguide.com/Movie-News/Julianne-Hough-Joins-1010823.aspx |work=TV Guide |date=October 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017033410/http://movies.tvguide.com/Movie-News/Julianne-Hough-Joins-1010823.aspx |archive-date=October 17, 2009 }}</ref>

Hough's first leading role was as Ariel Moore in the 2011 remake of the [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] film ''[[Footloose (2011 film)|Footloose]]'', opposite [[Kenny Wormald]] as Ren McCormack. Filming began in September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|first=Crystal|last=Tatum |url=http://www.rockdalecitizen.com/newtonnews/headlines/100171404.html |title=Georgia incentives nabbed 'Footloose' movie |work=Newton Citizen  |date=August 6, 2010 |access-date=October 11, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918125258/http://www.rockdalecitizen.com/newtonnews/headlines/100171404.html |archive-date=September 18, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film was released on October 14, 2011. Hough played the role of Sherrie Christian in the 2012 [[Rock of Ages (musical)|film adaptation]] of the Broadway musical ''[[Rock of Ages (2012 film)|Rock of Ages]]'', alongside [[Tom Cruise]], [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] and [[Malin Akerman]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|title='Rock of Ages' Stars Julianne Hough, Diego Boneta Train Their Voices for '80s Rock|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rock-ages-tom-cruise-julianne-hough-diego-boneta-338386|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 15, 2012|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305204001/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rock-ages-tom-cruise-julianne-hough-diego-boneta-338386|url-status=live}}</ref> That same year she filmed her starring role opposite [[Josh Duhamel]] in the romantic drama ''[[Safe Haven (film)|Safe Haven]]'', based on the [[Safe Haven (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Nicholas Sparks]], which was released on February 14, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2013-01-03 |title=Julianne Hough: 'I was abused' as a child |url=http://www.today.com/news/julianne-hough-i-was-abused-child-1C7806419 |access-date=2023-10-25 |website=TODAY.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Julianne Hough abused as a child, opens up as "Safe Haven" premieres - UPI.com |url=https://www.upi.com/blog/2013/01/03/Julianne-Hough-abused-as-a-child-opens-up-as-Safe-Haven-premieres/4801357227897/ |access-date=2023-10-25 |website=UPI |language=en}}</ref> Hough also starred in the comedy-drama ''[[Paradise (2013 American film)|Paradise]]'' as Lamb Mannerheim, which was released on October 18, 2013. She starred alongside [[Russell Brand]], who had previously co-starred with Hough in ''Rock of Ages''.

Hough starred as protagonist Mallory Rutledge in the 2015 thriller film ''[[Curve (film)|Curve]]'' opposite [[Teddy Sears]]. In the same year she appeared on business coach Lewis Howes's podcast where they had a discussion and it ended with him asking to [[salsa dance]] with her.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://lewishowes.com/podcast/julianne-hough/|title= JULIANNE HOUGH ON FINDING YOUR PASSION AND FOLLOWING YOUR PURPOSE|website= Lewis Howes.com|date= March 9, 2015|access-date= May 22, 2022|archive-date= July 3, 2022|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220703122205/https://lewishowes.com/podcast/julianne-hough/|url-status= live}}</ref> Hough returned to musical performances portraying the role of Sandy Young for [[Fox (network)|Fox]]'s [[Grease Live!|live television presentation]] of the musical ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'' on January 31, 2016.<ref name="grease">{{cite web|first=Matt|last=Webb Mitovitch|url=http://tvline.com/2015/01/17/fox-grease-musical-cast-julianne-hough-vanessa-hudgens|title=Fox's Live ''Grease'' Musical Casts Julianne Hough, Vanessa Hudgens|work=TVLine|date=January 17, 2015|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=February 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221233453/http://tvline.com/2015/01/17/fox-grease-musical-cast-julianne-hough-vanessa-hudgens/|url-status=live}}</ref> Hough and brother Derek hosted the 2016 ''[[Disney Parks|The Wonderful World of Disney: Magical Holiday Celebration]]'' and ''[[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade|The Disney Parks' Magical Christmas Celebration]]''. It was televised by ABC on Thanksgiving night, November 24, and Christmas Day, December 25. The Hough siblings introduced performances by [[Garth Brooks]], [[Trisha Yearwood]] and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. A companion holiday album, ''Disney Channel Holiday Hits'', was released November 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Ruth|last=Kinane|title=Disney Holiday Specials to Feature Kelly Clarkson, Julianne and Derek Hough, and More|url=http://ew.com/article/2016/11/02/disney-holiday-specials-julianne-hough-kelly-clarkson/|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |location=Des Moines, Iowa|date=November 2, 2016|access-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Robert|last=Bianco|title=TV tonight: 'Disney Christmas Celebration,' 'Richard III'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/columnist/criticscorner/2016/12/25/december-25-critics-corner/94813522/|work=[[USA Today]]|location=Tysons Corner, Virginia|date=November 2, 2016|access-date=January 23, 2017|archive-date=August 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829034106/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/columnist/criticscorner/2016/12/25/december-25-critics-corner/94813522/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2018, she was cast as Jolene in the episode of the same name from the [[Netflix]] anthology series ''[[Dolly Parton's Heartstrings (TV series)|Heartstrings]]'', based on the [[Dolly Parton]] [[Jolene (song)|song]].<ref name="Jolene">{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Rick|title=Dolly Parton Netflix Series 'Heartstrings' Sets Cast for 'Jolene'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/dolly-partons-netflix-series-heartstrings-sets-cast-jolene-1157002|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=January 2, 2018|date=November 1, 2018|archive-date=November 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181101200812/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/dolly-partons-netflix-series-heartstrings-sets-cast-jolene-1157002|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 11, 2019, it was announced that Hough had joined the NBC talent competition series ''[[America's Got Talent]]''.<ref name="agt host">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/americas-got-talent-terry-crews-1.27269600|title=Terry Crews to host 'America's Got Talent,' with Julianne Hough and Gabrielle Union joining as judges|publisher=Newsday|date=February 13, 2019|access-date=February 17, 2019|archive-date=February 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217142621/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/americas-got-talent-terry-crews-1.27269600|url-status=live}}</ref> However, she was announced to be exiting in November 22 in the same year after one season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|title=Gabrielle Union, Julianne Hough Out at 'America's Got Talent' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/gabrielle-union-julianne-hough-out-at-americas-got-talent-1203413880/amp/|website=Variety|access-date=November 23, 2019|date=November 22, 2019|archive-date=November 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123044242/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/gabrielle-union-julianne-hough-out-at-americas-got-talent-1203413880/amp/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2020, Hough partnered with entertainment company Meet Cute for a three-part ''Transformation'' podcast series. Meet Cute, along with Hough's production banner, Canary House Productions, wrote, executive produced, and voice acted in the series. As the title of the series suggests, ''Transformation'' aligns with Canary House's mission to impact lives through stories of transformation, self-discovery and identity.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ramos |first1=Dino-Ray |date=2020-11-11 |title=Julianne Hough Teams With Naomi Shah's Meet Cute For 'Transformation' Podcast Series |url=https://deadline.com/2020/11/julianne-hough-naomi-shah-meet-cute-transformation-podcast-series-1234613125/ |access-date=2022-10-18 |website=Deadline |language=en-US |archive-date=October 18, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221018161744/https://deadline.com/2020/11/julianne-hough-naomi-shah-meet-cute-transformation-podcast-series-1234613125/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Broadway debut ===
Hough made her [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] debut as Dusty in Selina Fillinger's comedic play ''[[POTUS: Or, Behind Every Great Dumbass Are Seven Women Trying to Keep Him Alive]]''. Performances began on April 14, 2022, at the [[Shubert Theatre (Broadway)|Shubert Theatre]].<ref name="{POTUS">{{cite web|last=Culwell-Block|first=Logan|title=Vanessa Williams, Rachel Dratch, Lilli Cooper, More to Star in POTUS On Broadway|url=https://playbill.com/article/vanessa-williams-rachel-dratch-lilli-cooper-more-to-star-in-potus-on-broadway|website=[[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]]|access-date=March 2, 2022|date=March 1, 2022|archive-date=March 1, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220301230759/https://www.playbill.com/article/vanessa-williams-rachel-dratch-lilli-cooper-more-to-star-in-potus-on-broadway|url-status=live}}</ref> Hough received rave reviews for her comic performance with ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' declaring, "Julianne Hough is particularly mesmerizing...[she] could easily be a mere stereotype, but she surprises at every turn."<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://ew.com/theater/potus-on-broadway-is-a-foulmouthed-political-funhouse-farce/|title= POTUS on Broadway is a foulmouthed political funhouse farce|magazine= [[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date= May 22, 2022}}</ref>

Hough hosted the first hour of the [[75th Tony Awards]] alongside [[Darren Criss]] which was aired on [[Paramount+]]. ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised her hosting capabilities writing, "[she] delighted us with her endearing eagerness to put on a show."<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/13/theater/best-worst-tony-awards.html|title= Best and Worst Moments of the 75th Tony Awards|website= [[The New York Times]]|date= June 13, 2022|access-date= June 13, 2022|last1= Green|first1= Jesse|last2= Phillips|first2= Maya|last3= Soloski|first3= Alexis|last4= Collins-Hughes|first4= Laura|last5= Vincentelli|first5= Elisabeth|last6= Testa|first6= Jessica|archive-date= June 13, 2022|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220613090812/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/13/theater/best-worst-tony-awards.html|url-status= live}}</ref> 
Critic Elizabeth Vincentelli also praised her adding, "she who didn't miss a step...[she] had a sparkly showbiz quality peppered with an adorably enthusiastic nerdiness".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/13/theater/best-worst-tony-awards.html|title= Best and Worst Moments from the 75th Tony Awards|website= [[The New York Times]]|date= June 13, 2022|access-date= June 13, 2022|last1= Green|first1= Jesse|last2= Phillips|first2= Maya|last3= Soloski|first3= Alexis|last4= Collins-Hughes|first4= Laura|last5= Vincentelli|first5= Elisabeth|last6= Testa|first6= Jessica|archive-date= June 13, 2022|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220613090812/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/13/theater/best-worst-tony-awards.html|url-status= live}}</ref> She also presented [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book of a Musical]] on the main telecast which aired on [[CBS]]. She has since returned hosting the "Act One" Pre-Show [[Tony Awards]] in [[76th Tony Awards|2023]] with [[Skylar Astin]] and in [[77th Tony Awards|2024]] with [[Utkarsh Ambudkar]].
<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lifestyle/arts/tonys-2023-act-one-hosts-julianne-hough-skylar-astin-1235509231/|title= Julianne Hough, Skylar Astin To Host Tonys Preshow as More Details Emerge About Unscripted Main Ceremony|website= [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date= June 7, 2023|accessdate= June 4, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://playbill.com/article/julianne-hough-utkarsh-ambudkar-will-host-2024-the-tony-awards-act-one|title= Julianne Hough, Utkarsh Ambudkar Will Host 2024 The Tony Awards: Act One|website= Playbill|accessdate= June 4, 2024}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In October 2013, Hough told the ''[[New York Post]]'' that although she was no longer a practicing member of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], she was glad that she was raised in the church.<ref>{{citation|first=Jane|last=Ridley|url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/12/former-mormon-julianne-hough-has-come-a-long-way/|title=Julianne Hough: From Mormon to wild child|work=[[New York Post]]|location=New York City|date=October 12, 2013|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=June 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200606060704/https://nypost.com/2013/10/12/former-mormon-julianne-hough-has-come-a-long-way/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Hough dated fellow country singer [[Chuck Wicks]] from August 2008 to November 2009; when the two had a mutual break-up, it inspired Hough's song "[[Is That So Wrong]]".<ref>{{cite web |first=Katie |last=Kauss |title=Chuck Wicks Helps Raise $25,000 for Charity |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20255145,00.html |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]  |location=Des Moines, Iowa |date=January 26, 2009 |access-date=October 24, 2014 |archive-date=November 1, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101090158/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20255145,00.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Katie|last=Kauss|title=Source: Julianne Hough and Chuck Wicks Split|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20318934,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|location=Des Moines, Iowa|date=November 10, 2009|access-date=October 24, 2014|archive-date=November 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101084531/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20318934,00.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Hough dated [[Ryan Seacrest]] from April 2010 to March 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shira |first=Dahvi |title=Ryan Seacrest & Julianne Hough Getting 'More Serious' |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20396092,00.html |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]  |location=Des Moines, Iowa |date=June 22, 2010 |access-date=October 3, 2012 |archive-date=April 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419143841/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20396092,00.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Alanna|last=Conaway|title=Julianne Hough Dishes on Meeting Ryan Seacrest|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/julianne-hough-ryan-seacrest-dating-chuck-wicks/|work=[[Taste of Country]]|location=Greenwich, Connecticut|date=August 2, 2012|access-date=October 3, 2012|archive-date=October 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007071615/http://tasteofcountry.com/julianne-hough-ryan-seacrest-dating-chuck-wicks/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Tauber |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20682930,00.html |title=Julianne Hough Gets 'Friends Therapy' After Ryan Seacrest Split |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]  |location=Des Moines, Iowa |date=March 17, 2013 |access-date=February 17, 2014 |archive-date=February 22, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222061530/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20682930,00.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> In February 2014, it was revealed that she had begun dating [[National Hockey League|NHL]] player [[Brooks Laich]], then of the [[Washington Capitals]], in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Rothman |title=Julianne Hough and Her Boyfriend Can't Stop Gushing About Each Other |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/julianne-hough-boyfriend-stop-gushing/story?id=22602981 |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=February 20, 2014 |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719173419/https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/julianne-hough-boyfriend-stop-gushing/story?id=22602981 |url-status=live }}</ref> The couple announced their engagement on August 18, 2015,<ref>{{cite news |first=Esther |last=Lee |title=Julianne Hough is Engaged! |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/julianne-hough-is-engaged-to-brooks-laich-2015188 |work=[[Us Weekly]] Company |location=New York City |date=August 18, 2015 |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=August 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810171244/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/julianne-hough-is-engaged-to-brooks-laich-2015188 |url-status=live }}</ref> and were married on July 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite news |first=Julie |last=Jordan |title=Julianne Hough Is Married! The DWTS Judge Weds NHL Star Brooks Laich in an Elegant Outdoor Idaho Ceremony |url=http://people.com/celebrity/julianne-hough-is-married-the-dwts-judge-weds-nhl-star-brooks-laich-in-an-elegant-outdoor-idaho-ceremony/ |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |location=Des Moines, Iowa |date=July 8, 2017 |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=July 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709061007/http://people.com/celebrity/julianne-hough-is-married-the-dwts-judge-weds-nhl-star-brooks-laich-in-an-elegant-outdoor-idaho-ceremony/ |url-status=live }}</ref> They separated in 2020, but later attempted to reconcile.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last1=Jordan |first1 = Julie | last2 = Chiu | first2 = Melody | last3 = Corinthios | first3 = Aurelie | last4 = Falcone | first4 = Dana|title=Julianne Hough and Brooks Laich Separate After 2 Years of Marriage|url=https://people.com/tv/julianne-hough-brooks-laich-split/|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|language=EN|date=May 29, 2020|access-date=July 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/julianne-hough-brooks-laich-are-giving-things-another-shot/ | title = Julianne Hough and Brooks Laich Are 'Giving Things Another Shot' 3 Months After Split | first1 = Sarah | last1 = Hearon | date = September 30, 2020 | magazine = [[US Weekly]] | access-date = October 3, 2020}}</ref> Hough filed for divorce on November 2, 2020; the divorce was finalized on February 22, 2022.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/celebrity/julianne-hough-files-for-divorce-from-brooks-laich-5-months-after-announcing-separation/ar-BB1aDaJ5 | title = Julianne Hough Files for Divorce from Brooks Laich 5 Months After Announcing Separation | work = [[People (magazine)|People]] | via = [[MSN]] | date = November 2, 2020 | first1 = Natalie | last1 = Stone | access-date = November 3, 2020 | archive-date = June 29, 2023 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20230629174448/https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/celebrity/julianne-hough-files-for-divorce-from-brooks-laich-5-months-after-announcing-separation/ar-BB1aDaJ5 | url-status = live }}</ref>

Hough attracted controversy in October 2013 when she donned [[blackface]] as part of a Halloween costume depicting [[Uzo Aduba]]'s character [[Crazy Eyes (Orange Is the New Black)|Suzanne "Crazy Eyes" Warren]] from the [[Netflix]] comedy-drama ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cavan |last=Sieczkowski |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/29/derek-hough-blackface_n_4175160.html |title=Derek Hough Defends Sister In Blackface Controversy |work=[[Huffington Post]] |location=New York City |date=October 29, 2013 |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=April 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421223805/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/29/derek-hough-blackface_n_4175160.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Hollie |last=McKay |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2013/10/28/julianne-hough-slammed-for-donning-black-face-Halloween-costume/ |title=Julianne Hough slammed for donning 'black face' Halloween costume |work=[[Fox News]] |location=New York City |date=October 28, 2013 |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415083934/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2013/10/28/julianne-hough-slammed-for-donning-black-face-halloween-costume/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Hough later apologized, writing on [[Twitter]], "I realize my costume hurt and offended people and I truly apologize."<ref>{{cite news|first=Maria|last=Vultaggio|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/julianne-hough-blackface-Halloween-my-costume-hurt-offended-people-i-truly-apologize-1442930|title=Julianne Hough Blackface Halloween: 'My Costume Hurt And Offended People And I Truly Apologize'|work=[[International Business Times]]|location=New York City|date=October 27, 2013|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-date=February 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228232121/http://www.ibtimes.com/julianne-hough-blackface-halloween-my-costume-hurt-offended-people-i-truly-apologize-1442930|url-status=live}}</ref>

She was diagnosed with [[endometriosis]] in 2008, and went public with it to help de-stigmatize the conditions surrounding the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/julianne-hough-shares-how-debilitating-endometriosis-is-and-how-she-copes-with-the-pain|title=Julianne Hough Shares How "Debilitating" Endometriosis Is and How She Copes With the Pain|publisher=Glamour|first=Sara|last=Gaynes Levy|date=March 23, 2017|access-date=April 2, 2018|archive-date=April 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403051356/https://www.glamour.com/story/julianne-hough-shares-how-debilitating-endometriosis-is-and-how-she-copes-with-the-pain|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/julianne-hough-endometriosis_us_5aa2a2cbe4b086698a9d2274|title=Julianne Hough Lived In Pain For Years Because Of Endometriosis|publisher=Huffington Post|first=Lindsay|last=Holmes|date=March 9, 2018|access-date=April 2, 2018|archive-date=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402021252/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/julianne-hough-endometriosis_us_5aa2a2cbe4b086698a9d2274|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.today.com/health/julianne-hough-endometriosis-i-just-thought-it-was-normal-t116059 |title=Julianne Hough opens up about endometriosis: 'I just thought it was normal' |work=[[Today (American TV program)|Today]] |date=9 September 2017 |access-date=21 January 2021 |author=Murray, Rheana}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-04-23 |title=Julianne Hough Won't Let Endometriosis Stop Her From Having a Family With Brooks Laich: "We've Discussed Options" |url=https://www.endofound.org/julianne-hough-wont-let-endometriosis-stop-her-from-having-a-family-with-brooks-laich-weve-discussed |access-date=2023-12-31 |website=Endometriosis : Causes - Symptoms - Diagnosis - and Treatment |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Olya |first=Gabrielle |date=March 24, 2017 |title=Julianne Hough Opens Up About Her Struggle with Endometriosis |url=https://people.com/health/julianne-hough-endometriosis/ |access-date=2023-12-31 |website=Peoplemag |language=en}}</ref>

Hough describes herself as "not straight."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/julianne-hough-describes-moment-she-140459188.html|title=Julianne Hough describes the moment she told husband Brooks Laich 'I'm not straight'|website=[[Yahoo! News]]|first=Georgia|last=Slater|date=1 August 2019|access-date=30 May 2020|archive-date=August 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801173155/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/julianne-hough-describes-moment-she-140459188.html|url-status=live}}</ref> She co-owns a wine brand with actress [[Nina Dobrev]] called Fresh Vine Wine.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Drinking Fresh Vine Wine With Julianne Hough And Nina Dobrev |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/adammorganstern/2022/11/01/drinking-fresh-vine-wines-with-julianne-hough-and-nina-dobrev/?sh=47e1b3997fa1 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=[[Forbes]] }}</ref>

